Biology, Chemistry and physics of the ocean</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>54465183033b95.94443883-2</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partnerContribution>My partners (Stephanie Dutkiewicz, Mick Follows and Ben Ward) have helped me setup this new model and kept on developing the representation for nitrogen fixers.</gtr:partnerContribution><gtr:piContribution>I am developing a new model to represent diversity of nitrogen fixers and coccolithophores in the global ocean using the MIT-Darwin model.</gtr:piContribution><gtr:sector>Academic/University</gtr:sector></gtr:collaborationOutput></gtr:collaborationOutputs><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>Coccolithophores are one of most important marine phytoplankton. They are dominant in large part of the ocean easily seen from satellite imagery. Not only because these organisms are a dominant phytoplankton type in the ocean, coccolithophores are key players of the climate via the uptake of atmospheric CO2 because they calcify. However we do not know why coccolithophores calcify. Here we have gathered any evidence from laboratory experiments and in-situ observations to determine the hypothetical functions of calcification in coccolithophores. We have then developed a ocean model of coccolithophores to test the different functions of calcification. We find that coccolithophores calcify for different reasons for different regions of the ocean.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>Knowing that coccolithophores calcify for different reasons will help others to better asses the impact of global warming on these phytoplankton community.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>199603B4-E0F0-4CD4-84DD-AAB654A9E615</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>54465b958b0558.14833752</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Environment</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluence